(1, ' ', '7', 'Research and Development (R&D) and Technology Transfer Activities of the DOST Research and Development Institutes (RDIs)', 'Dr. Annabelle V. Briones', '24', '9', '20,26,27,30,31', 'Engr. Maria Teresa B. De Guzman', '3,4,5,7,8,38,39', '2019-02-27', '2019-10-04', 'Office of the Director,Planning and Management Information Systems,Chemicals and Energy Division,Environment and Biotechnology Division,Food Processing Division', '<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Please see attached <strong>Annex A</strong>.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Overseer: Engr. Maria Teresa B. De Guzman -&nbsp; Director, IAS</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Secretariat:</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Engr. Arnaldo C. Reyes - OIC, Management Audit Division, IAS</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Edgardo P. Catorce, Jr. - Internal Auditor IV, IAS</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Marian C. Gelera - Internal Auditor III, IAS</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Kristine Joy M. Tablizo - Internal Auditor III, IAS</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Jannin G. Trinidad - Internal Auditor II, IAS</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Rebecca Rose B. Javier - Internal Auditor II, IAS</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Hersa Jazzica E. Olid - Computer Operator II, IAS</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Ann Crisiene R. Reducto - Project Assistant I, IAS</span></p>', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">The Industrial Technology and Development Institute (ITDI) is one of the Research and Development Institutes (RDIs) of the Department of Science and Technology (DOST) mandated to undertake applied research and development to generate new knowledge, technologies, and innovations in the field of industrial manufacturing, mineral processing, and energy; conduct knowledge translation or technology transfer and commercialization; and provide technical services, tests and analyses, and metrology to ensure international traceability of the national units of measure as per ITDI Rationalization Plan dated February 5, 2010.&nbsp; ITDI is composed of eleven (11) divisions namely: Chemical and energy Division (CED), Environment and Biotechnology Division (EBD), food processing Division (FPD), Materials Science Division (MSD), Packaging Technology Division (PTD), Technological Services Division (TSD), Standards and Testing Division, National Metrology Division (NMD), Administrative Division (AD), Financial Management Division (FMD) and Planning and Management Information Systems Division (PMIS). However, two (2) of these divisions, STD and NMD, were not covered in the scope of the audit.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Objectives:</strong></span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">To assess the effectiveness of the internal control system in the conduct of R&amp;D and technology transfer activities and examine the degree of compliance with mandate, established objectives, systems, processes, and government laws, rules, regulations, policies, procedures and contractual obligations;</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">To evaluate the outcome, output, process and input to determine whether the R&amp;D and technology transfer programs, projects and activities of the RDIs are effective, efficient, ethical, and economical, and are delivering the outputs based on the developed quantitative metrics of DOST known as 6Ps (Publications, Patents, Products, People Services, Places and Partnerships) and the Baldrige criteria for performance excellence;</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">To ascertain the reliability of financial reporting, appropriateness of measures taken and adequacy of monitoring and evaluation systems; and</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">To identify the best practices of the RDIs that can be the basis for assessing policies, strategies, structures and practices leading to a better informed decision-making, courses of action, resource allocation and accountability and this will serve as standards of other DOST-RDIs.</span></li>\r\n</ol>', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Good Points</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Planning Division&nbsp;</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">1.&nbsp; </span><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\">The ITDI Management through its Planning Division has initiated a strategic planning process in 2018 that has not been done in the past by the Institute. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The</span><strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> ITDI&rsquo;s first agency-wide strategic planning consisting of a series of activities started with a survey conducted among the employees, gathering of feedback from customers and the PESTLE analysis on the organization.In Jan 2019, the ITDI management team agreed on a vision, mission, core values, goals, and strategies which were the basis of the various divisions identifying program/activities/projects (PAPs) for 2020-2024.&nbsp; The first draft of the Strategic Plan is targetted to go through Focus Group Discussions among the divisions with the presence of the Industry Advisory Committee (IAC) and the first ITDI Strategic Plan will be finalized by the end of 2019. In the previous administrations, only annual operational plans were prepared by the Institute based on the DOST\'s Strategic Plan.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">2. </span></strong></span><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">The Planning Division paved the way to have a common mechanism in evaluating program/project proposals and completed projects. <strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As one of their initiated improvements, the Planning Division facilitated the development of a set of criteria in 2018&nbsp; for the Technical Review Committee (TRC) in evaluating programs/projects which were not available before. Likewise, a common process for screening program/project proposals and evaluating completed undertakings is now being done. ITDI submits for PCIEERD&rsquo;s technical review its GAA program/project proposals, ongoing and completed undertakings while engaging TAPI in a review of completed projects. It continues to &ldquo;tweak&rdquo; its old processes to adopt new techniques and concepts such as the &ldquo;business model canvas&rdquo; and the &ldquo;value proposition canvas&rdquo; in program/project development.&nbsp;</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">R&amp;D Divisions</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">3. ITDI&rsquo;s R&amp;D Divisions implement and monitor the Staff Development based on the approved ITDI&rsquo;s Annual Training Plan which includes core competency of the personnel, level of gaps, area of training/study for the degree and non-degree programs. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Staff Development plan <strong>(Annex B) </strong>developed by the R&amp;D Divisions raised their overall staff expertise and acquire a broad set of skills that helped them guide the organization through change. Case-in-point: PTD training on Sustainable and Safe Packaging.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">4. The ITDI was able to help promote the culture of S&amp;T among students. The R&amp;D Divisions mentor students from science and engineering courses as well as from senior high school by accepting students to do their immersion in their laboratories and in sharing their laboratories for their thesis. In 2018, ITDI benefitted a total of 1,311 students.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Table 1. No. of Students Assisted per R&amp;D Division</strong></span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 50.1152%; height: 110px;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 58.1562%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">ITDI\'s R&amp;D Division</span></strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 45.906%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">No. of Students Assisted (2018)&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 58.1562%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Chemicals and Energy Division (CED)</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 45.906%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">569</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 18px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 58.1562%; height: 18px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Environment and Biotechnology Division (EBD)</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 45.906%; height: 18px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">300</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 24px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 58.1562%; height: 24px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Food Processing Division (FPD)</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 45.906%; height: 24px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">202</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 58.1562%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Materials Science Division (MSD)</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 45.906%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">131</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 58.1562%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Packaging Technology Division (PTD)</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 45.906%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">109</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 58.1562%; text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Total</span></strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 45.906%; text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">1,311</span></strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">5. The R&amp;D Divisions were able to help the industry especially the MSMEs through the technical assistance that they offer.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>Table 2. Total No. of MSMEs Assisted by CED and EBD for CY 2012-2018</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 56.2332%; height: 54px;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 14.8212%; text-align: center; height: 17px;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Division</span></strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 28.0633%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Technical Service</span></strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 23.9101%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Total No. of MSMEs assisted (2012-2018)</span></strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 14.8212%; text-align: center; height: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">CED</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 28.0633%; height: 20px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Energy Audit</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 23.9101%; height: 20px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">142</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 14.8212%; text-align: center; height: 17px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">EBD</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 28.0633%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Environmental Technology Verification</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 23.9101%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">121</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Materials Science Division (MSD)&nbsp;</span></span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">6. The MSD responds significantly to the needs of the industries through the Advanced Device and Materials and Testing Laboratory (ADMATEL) that provides failure analysis and materials testing facilities for local industries. The clients of ADMATEL are comprised of the semiconductor and electronics industries, plastics/packaging, metals, paints and coating, construction, services, food, wire manufacturing, petrochemical, agriculture, textile, telecommunications, shoes, piping, leisure products, industrial gas, clothing, chemical, battery, automotive, air conditioning, and trading, as well as the academe and government agencies. The table below shows the increasing income and number of firms assisted per year by the ADMATEL for CY 2013-2018.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Table 3. No. of Firms Assisted and Income of ADMATEL Per Year</span></strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 40.7591%; height: 121px;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 18px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 11.6838%; text-align: center; height: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Year</strong></span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 18.1177%; height: 18px; text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">No. of Firms Assisted Per Year</span></strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.3958%; height: 18px; text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Income Per Year (Php)</span></strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 18px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 11.6838%; text-align: center; height: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">2013</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 18.1177%; height: 18px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">44</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.3958%; height: 18px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">3,416,000</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 11.6838%; text-align: center; height: 17px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">2014</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 18.1177%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">88</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.3958%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">3,790,750</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 11.6838%; text-align: center; height: 17px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">2015</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 18.1177%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">107</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.3958%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">5,007,900</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 11.6838%; text-align: center; height: 17px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">2016</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 18.1177%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">126</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.3958%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">9,887,720</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 11.6838%; text-align: center; height: 17px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">2017</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 18.1177%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">138</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.3958%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">15,706,750</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 11.6838%; text-align: center; height: 17px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">2018</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 18.1177%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">139</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.3958%; height: 17px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">17,708,200</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">The MSD follows the industry trends through the conduct of R&amp;D in advanced materials such as nanotechnology products, nanomaterials, and nano-enabled products. <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Case-in-point: Biodegradable nanocomposites, ultrafiltration/nanofiltration hollow fiber membrane, and rainwater collection system.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Packaging Technology Division (PTD)</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">7. Starting as a DOST flagship program in packaging in 1999, the ITDI&rsquo;s packaging group successfully transitioned to become a full-fledged ITDI R&amp;D division institutionalized in 2009 as the </span>Packaging Technology Division (PTD)<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The division is guided by a roadmap which is regularly reviewed and updated every 5 years. The said roadmap outlines the development plans for the division especially the priority R&amp;D activities that they need to pursue.&nbsp; </span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">PTD conducts benchmarking activities, which sets a clear vision/goal for the Division and <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">was able to achieve its vision of being recognized in the field of packaging technology, design, testing, and engineering.</span>&nbsp;They were<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> able to identify its packaging innovation and research direction by continually updating its roadmap. They also le</span></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ad the MSMEs in the package development of their products and significantly contribute to their success through numerous packaging technology that caters to different industries. Furthermore, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">PTD </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">R&amp;D activities and facility upgrading are directly focused toward achieving the roadmap target deliverables, i.e., simulation packaging testing and green packaging lab.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Locally, PTD was recognized not only in DOST but also by other departments/line agencies, such as the DTI, and the private sector as well.&nbsp; Internationally, they are also starting to gain recognition because of the successful holding of the Asian Packaging Conference which was attended by packaging industries worldwide. Moreover, </span>PTD was nominated as one of the top 10 finalists out of 2000 entries in the 2016 R&amp;D Awards.&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The design entry for this award is the Pack of Hope, the first Ready to Eat (RTE) Chicken Arroz Caldo as the first stage disaster relief to address the immediate hunger and thirst of calamity survivors within 48 hours. This was used during the rescue of the victims of typhoon Yolanda. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Through this recognition, PTD was able to source additional external funding from the Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA).</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Technological Services Division (TSD)</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">8. The </span>TSD<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">&nbsp;staff learned from various training abroad (i.</span>e., Technology Audit and Quicklook from University of Texas Austin, and Technology Readiness Assessment (TRA) from US Air Force). The culture of continuous learning and taking risks in trying out new strategies and tools has developed. Knowledge acquired is shared among the staff and even to other DOST agencies.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">9. The </span>TSD<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;has tied up with the Department of Foreign Affairs which provided technical assistance to other countries through the conduct of livelihood training (e.g. Vanuatu and East Timor) using DOST technologies in 2012, 2015 and 2019.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">10. The </span>Technological Services Division (TSD)<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> led the standardization of fees and charges for training and technical services not just in ITDI but also in the DOST System.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">11. With a limited GAA budget, Technological Services Division (TSD) is actively proposing projects to different funding agencies (i.e., PCIEERD and TAPI) to be able to participate in various local and international exhibits (e.g. IFEX Philippines, Taipei International Food Show) and other technology transfer activities such as technology forums.&nbsp; Through such projects, they were also able to source out funds for their high-quality flyers/brochures for the promotion of their technologies and corporate branding.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">12. In an effort to transfer more ITDI technologies,</span> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">the</span> Technological Services Division (TSD) <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">develops a technology package composed of two or more complementing technologies (e.g., RTE Arroz Caldo with free training on packaging design and labeling plus heat penetration test) to make it palatable to prospective adopters.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">13<strong>.</strong> I<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">TDI</span><strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Management took a proactive approach in promoting their technologies during an international food exhibit (e.g., IFEX) by not only showcasing the ITDI technologies to the venue but personally introducing ITDI technologies from one participating booth to another where they think ITDI technologies would complement other products/technologies.</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">14. The </span>TSD <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">provides holistic approach during pre-technology transfer activity as the three TSD sections (e.g., Business Development Section, Training Section, Engineering Services Section) are involved when meeting or visiting their clients to assess the overall needs in terms of training, equipment, layout, etc.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Finance and Administrative Division (FAD)</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">15.&nbsp; The </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Property and Procurement Section puts sticker tags with inventory numbers to all semi-expendable PPEs and inventories for them for easy monitoring and tracking of accountable personnel. In case of resignation or retirement, these semi-expendable items issued to them are returned to the Section for them to be cleared from office accountabilities. This is the only system of monitoring semi-expendable supplies, materials and equipment existing in DOST.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">16. To facilitate the collection process, an information system called Official Receipt Database Management System (ORDBMS) for the collection process was developed by the Cash Section for faster processing and generation of collection reports. They also use LDDAP-ADA Database Management System through MS-access in order to check and verify the status of disbursement (preparation of check, check for release, already paid). The information systems internally-developed by the Cash Section are attached in <strong>Annex C</strong>. This is the only Cashier\'s office, so far, in DOST which has established and adopted IT systems for faster and quality delivery of its services.&nbsp;</span></p>', '38', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-14 16:12:35', '2019-12-26 17:24:12', ' ', ' ', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(2, ' ', '17', 'Inventors\' Fund for CYs 2011-2018', 'Engr. Edgar I. Garcia', '49', '9', '3,5,51,38', 'Maria Teresa B. De Guzman', '', '2019-05-01', '2019-06-30', 'Technology Information and Promotion Division (TIPD),Invention Development Division (IDD),Investment and Business Operations Division (IBOD),Finance and Administrative Division (FAD)', '<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Auditees:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 415px;\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 218.516px;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Nora P. Gumia</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Rodelia R. Padilla</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Eileen S. Fernando</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Atty. Marion Ivy Decena</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Elizabeth I. Garcia</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Mr. Romeo M. Javate</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Rhoalyn D. Gacho</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 184.766px;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Mr. Rodel R. Oraciou</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Rosemarie L. Olaer</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Lilia B. Ferrer</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Florencia P. Pangilinan</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Josephine B. Ramos</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ms. Leilanie Casacop</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Technology Application institute (TAPI) is one of the Science and Technology Services Institute under the Department of Science and Technology (DOST). It was created by virtue of Executive Order No. 128 on January 30, 1987 and is mandated to promote the commercialization of technologies and market the services of other operating units of the Department. On April 28, 1992, the function of TAPI was expanded by virtue of Republic Act No. 7459, otherwise known as the&rdquo; Inventors and Invention Incentives Act of the Philippines&rdquo;. Among others, TAPI administers the Invention Development Assistance Fund (IDAF) for the initial experiments and prototype development and other invention-development related activities.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Objectives:</strong></span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">To review the systems and processes pertinent to the Invention Guarantee Fund (IGF) and Invention Development Assistance Fund (IDAF);</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">To evaluate the implementation of financial and related internal controls;</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">To assess the effectiveness of the outputs and of the government&rsquo;s investments in IGF and IDAF; and</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">To recommend realistic courses of action to protect the assets and control measures to prevent fraud and losses of any kind; among others, in the administration of TAPI&rsquo;s Inventors&rsquo; Fund.</span></li>\r\n</ol>', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Good Points:</strong></span></p>\r\n<ol style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">IDD created a project through TAPI-GIA to establish and Enforcement Unit which went after inventors with delinquent accounts. In order to demonstrate to COA their commitment to close delinquent accounts, the Enforcement Unit tracked down the location of the beneficiaries/grantees to arrange for the repayment or to gather information and proof if the inventor is unable to or is no longer capable of refunding the money. TAPI also developed enforcement guidelines (e.g., Memorandum Circular No. 2016-001, series of 2016- Revised Standard Policy and Procedures on Completion, Termination, Liquidation and Administrative Exhaustion of Remedies for Delinquent TAPI-GIA Projects) which are adopted by other divisions of the Institute. They also worked along with COA as they visit inventors even in the Yolanda stricken areas.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2. Biometric systems are installed in offices that require strict security to limit access to Division/Office personnel and to protect confidential records</span><strong>.</strong></span></p>', '5', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-15 15:01:24', '2019-11-26 08:34:04', ' ', ' ', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '');
INSERT INTO `form_content` (`id`, `form_001_id`, `auditfinding_no`, `subof`, `author_id`, `audit_area`, `custom_auditarea`, `sub_auditarea`, `auditfinding`, `auditrecommend`, `auditmanageaction`, `action_by`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `archive_status`, `main_area`, `custom_subauditarea`) VALUES
(1, '1', 43, '', '5', ' ', 'Administrative Management', 'Submission of RPCPPE', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Late submission of the Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE)</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Chapter 10, Section 38 of Government Accounting Manual (GAM) Volume 1 states that the entity shall have a periodic physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), which shall be done annually and presented on the RPCPPE as of December 31 of each year. This shall be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of the following year. Equipment found at station and losses discovered during the physical count shall be reported to the Accounting Division/Unit for proper accounting/recording.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">To comply with this requirements, they have created an Inventory Committee, through ITDI Special Order No. 078, Series of 2019 <strong>(Annex H)</strong>, which is assigned to assist the Institute in conducting physical count of all PPEs and Semi-expendable items owned by ITDI. Schedules on the conduct of activities are provided by the Property and Procurement Management Section to the Committee. However, although schedules and members of the Committee are set, the Section is still challenged in the preparation of RPCPPE because of its limited personnel and postponement of some physical count schedules. Property tags and stickers are provided not only to the PPE items as accounted in the books but also to the Semi-expendable items that are considered as inventories and booked as expense when issued.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">During the interview at the Property and Procurement Section, they mentioned that all equipment, including those that are valued P15,000 and below and accounted as semi-expendable items, were provided with property tags or stickers which takes time during their physical count. Although putting property tags and stickers for semi-expendable items creates an easier monitoring mechanism for the Agency, this do not compensate the late conduct of physical count and late submission of RPCPPEs to the concerned oversight agency. Although the RPCI format in GAM provided a column for &ldquo;Stock Number&rdquo;, it does not require that property stickers/tags be attached to the semi-expendable items. Stock number can be accessed through the monitoring tracker (excel format) maintained by the Section.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Table __: Submission of PRCPPEs</span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 81.6688%;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 38.3692%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Year</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 43.2996%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Date of Submission</strong></span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 38.3692%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">2012</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 43.2996%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">April 2, 2013</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 38.3692%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">2013</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 43.2996%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">March 12, 2014</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 38.3692%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">2014</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 43.2996%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">To be retrieved from COA</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 38.3692%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">2015</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 43.2996%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">May 17, 2019</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 38.3692%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">2016</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 43.2996%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">March 10, 2017</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 38.3692%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">2017</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 43.2996%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">February 1, 2018</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 38.3692%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">2018</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 43.2996%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">May 23, 2019</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">As revealed during the interview, personnel from the Property and Procurement Section admitted that they failed to meet the deadline in submitting the RPCPPE. They only have one (1) staff, Administrative Officer III, who is fully assigned for the functions of Property Management, Inventory and Disposal, and assisted by the Section Chief. </span><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">This is due to the two unfilled positions of the Property and Procurement Section. Currently, only one personnel and the Section Head are monitoring and conducting activities concerning property administration and management.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Also, Appendix 73 of GAM Volume II provides the specified format for PRCPPE. As mentioned in the instructions of filling-up the form, it shall be certified correct by the Inventory Committee Chair and Members, approved by the Head of Agency/Entity or his/her Authorized Representative, and verified by the COA Representative. Based on the copies of PRCPPEs provided, these were only signed by three (3) ITDI personnel: PPS staff who acted as the preparer, noted by the Section Chief and approved by the Deputy Director. These were not signed by the Inventory Committee and a representative from COA.</span></p>', '', ' ', ' ', '', '2019-08-14 16:47:00', '2020-01-06 15:06:18', '0', '2', ' '),
(2, '1', 44, '', '5', 'Administrative Management Division', ' ', 'Physical Count of PPEs', '<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Property distributed to Regional offices as part of the OneLab project were not physically counted</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">GAM Volume 1 and PD 1445 require the periodic conduct of physical count of PPEs. Furthermore, to support the agencies budgetary requests for Capital Outlay, particularly the PPEs component, reiterates the need to conduct physical count on all PPES owned and managed by the offices.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">However, based on the Audit Team&rsquo;s interview with the Property and Procurement Management Section, the Inventory Committee was not able to physically count the PPEs distributed to the DOST Regional Offices for their Food Innovation Centers (FICs), thus creating doubt as to the integrity of the inventory report. They also mentioned during the interview that this is due to the limited funding of travelling and other related expenses entailed in the conduct of the activity and the schedules of the Inventory Committee. Although these PPEs were reported in their RPCPPEs, the responsibility in conducting physical counts and supervision were left with the concerned personnel from the DOST Regional Offices.</span></p>', '', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-14 16:50:45', '2019-08-16 14:43:32', '0', '1', ' '),
(3, '1', 45, '', '5', 'Administrative Management Division', ' ', 'Insurance Coverage', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Inadequate Insurance Coverage for ITDI buildings and its components</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">As specified in Section 2 of Republic Act No. 656, otherwise known as the Property Insurance Law, Property Insurance Fund was established in order to indemnify or compensate the Government for any damage to, or loss of, its properties due to fire, earthquake, storm and other casualties.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Furthermore, Section 5 of the same RA mentioned that every government, except a municipal government below first class, is hereby required to insure its properties, with the fund against any insurable risk and pay the premiums thereon, which, however, shall not exceed the premiums charged by private insurance companies.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">In the same manner, Section 11 expressed that each government shall include in its annual appropriation the amount necessary to cover premiums for the insurance of its properties during each fiscal period.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">During the audit, the Property and Procurement Management Section submitted copy of the GSIS Insurance Policy No. FI-GSISHO-0031145 covering the period November 15, 2018 to November 15, 2019. Based on the report, properties insured includes buildings and components amounting to P54,033,931.71 and P33,138,762. <strong>(Annex I)</strong>.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">As revealed by the Head of the Property and Procurement Section, the same observation was already raised to them by the Commission on Audit (COA). However, applying the principle of cost and benefit, they have proposed to replace the insurance coverage for &ldquo;floods&rdquo; to earthquake as the vicinity of ITDI buildings are not that prone to floods and landslides. Based on the GSIS Insurance Policy availed by the Institute, this was not considered when they renewed their insurance premiums in 2017 and 2018.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">The inadequacy of insurance coverage of building and other real properties does not only deprive ITDI of adequate protection against any damage or loss but also expose the Agency to risk of non-indemnification to unnecessary losses in the event of damage or loss caused by calamities such as earthquake, storms, flood and other causes beyond the insurance limit.</span></p>', '', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-14 16:52:14', '2019-11-26 14:12:43', '0', '2', ' '),
(5, '1', 48, '', '5', 'Administrative Management Division', ' ', 'GAM Formats', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Late adoption of formats required by GAM due to Property and Procurement Unit&rsquo;s non-involvement to trainings</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Government Accounting Manual (GAM) Volume 2 shows the Accounting Books, Registries, Records, Forms and Reports. Appendixes of the Manual that are related to the forms used by Property and Procurement Section include the following:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li>Supplies Ledger Card;</li>\r\n<li>Stock Card;</li>\r\n<li>Inventory Custodian Slip, Purchase Request;</li>\r\n<li>Purchase Order;</li>\r\n<li>Inspection and Acceptance Report;</li>\r\n<li>Requisition and Issue Slip;</li>\r\n<li>Report of Supplies and Materials issued;</li>\r\n<li>Waste Materials Report;</li>\r\n<li>Report on Physical Count of Inventories;</li>\r\n<li>Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms;</li>\r\n<li>Property Card;</li>\r\n<li>Property, Plant, and Equipment Ledger Card;</li>\r\n<li>Property Acknowledgement Receipt; and</li>\r\n<li>Report on the Physical</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As mentioned during the interview with the Property and Procurement Unit, they only adopted the GAM prescribed forms and format in March 2018. There are not compliant to GAM prescribed forms from the implementation of GAM in year 2015 until February 2018.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Since the Property and Procurement Section has no idea on the new formats and was not called to participate in GAM and COA-related trainings, they were not able to immediately adopt new forms aligned with the implementation of GAM.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">FAD personnel are equipped with trainings administered by COA and other oversight agencies. However, personnel from the Property and Procurement Sections were not involved during the Government Accounting Manual (GAM) Training organized by the DOST-Central Office in May 2016.</p>', '', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-14 16:53:40', '2019-08-16 14:44:20', '0', '1', ' '),
(6, '1', 46, '', '5', 'Administrative Management Division', ' ', 'Personnel Requirement', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Insufficient Staffing of Property and Procurement Personnel</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">National Budget Circular No. 2015-558 dated June 4, 2015 shows the guidelines in the organization and staffing of Procurement Units which requires the strengthening of the staffing of Procurement Units of agencies and provide adequate support to the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC).</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">As prescribed by the said Circular the organizational level of the procurement unit shall be as follows:</span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Annual Procurement Budget</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Department-level Agency</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Bureau-level Agency</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">GOCC/GFI</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">P5 billion and above</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Service</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Division</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Department</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Less than P5 billion</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Division</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Section&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Division</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">In the case of ITDI, Property and Procurement functions are lodged in one (1) section known as the Property and Procurement Management Section under the Administrative Division. Currently, as shown in their organizational Chart, there are seven (7) plantilla positions assigned to the Section, two (2) of which are unfilled as of May 2019 <strong>(Annex J)</strong>. Of the five (5) filled up positions, three (3) are assigned to Procurement Management, one (1) in Property Management and one (1) section Chief who supervises the two sub-sections.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Table __: Area of Assignment of the Property and Procurement Management Personnel</span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Name</strong></span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Position/SG</strong></span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Area of Assignment</strong></span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Rocheel Lee C. Deluta</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Administrative Officer V/18</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Section Chief</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Emerilyn A. Lava</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Administrative Officer III/14</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Property Management</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Jovielyn R. Pareja</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Administrative Officer I/10</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Procurement Management</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Vacant</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Administrative Assistant II/8</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Property Management</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Roda Mae O. Urmeneta</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Administrative Aide VI/6</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Procurement Management</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Vacant</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Administrative Aide VI/6</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Property Management</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Lorena R. Cacabelos</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Administrative Aide IV/4</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Procurement Management</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Because of the limited number of personnel and the urgency to process procurement needs, the Section is more focused on the Procurement Management function than the Property Management. In fact, they were delayed in conducting physical counts, submission of RPCPPE and unserviceable PPEs for disposal. However, it was mentioned during the interview that delays on the conduct of annual physical count and preparation of related reports will be processed and facilitated when two (2) vacant positions will be filled-up. Currently, these positions which were vacated in August 2018 and January 2019 are already scheduled for the ITDI&rsquo;s Selection Board Evaluation.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">In the same manner, ITDI constituted their Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat, separate from the Property and Procurement Management Section, who are directly reporting to the Officer-in-Charge of the Administrative Division. The Secretariat is chaired by the Administrative Officer V and Section Chief of the Records Section and assisted by Administrative Officer IV and Administrative Officer III. They are not part of the Property and Procurement Section and not doing responsibilities assigned to the Section but are solely focusing on BAC Secretariat activities and the consolidation of Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP).</span></p>', '', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-14 16:58:04', '2019-11-26 14:14:01', '0', '1', ' '),
(7, '1', 47, '', '5', 'Administrative Management Division', ' ', 'Account Reconciliation', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Unreconciled Balance of PPE Accounts</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards No. 17 prescribes the accounting treatment for property, plant, and equipment (PPE) so that users of financial statements can discern information about an entity&rsquo;s investment in its PPE and the changes in such investment. In the same manner, a periodic physical count of PPE shall be done annually and presented in the RPCPPE.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">During the audit, the Audit Team requested for the receiving copies of the RPCPPE submitted by the Agency from years 2012-2018. Also, they disclosed that record&rsquo;s reconciliation between the Accounting and Property and Procurement Sections were scheduled to address the variances in their records, However, after comparing the balances presented against those recorded in the Financial Statements, it was noted that there are material variances in the total amounts as presented below:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Table__: Comparison of PPE Balances per RPCPPE and Accounting Books</span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 424px;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 48px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; height: 95px; text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10