(19, '1', 15, '', '5', 'Administrative Management Division', ' ', 'Succession Plan', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong><em>There was no formal mechanism, procedures and guidelines to adopt and implement a Succession Plan.</em></strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">The Civil Service Commission issued Memorandum Circular No. 3 (CSC MC No. 3), series of 2012 on the Program to Institutionalize Meritocracy and Excellence in Human Resource Management (PRIME-HRM).&nbsp; The said MC directs all government agencies to inculcate meritocracy and excellence in public service, including the establishment of an Agency Succession Plan.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Furthermore, the CSC PRIME HRM prescribes that a Succession Development Plan should be prepared by government institutions. This plan should be a proactive and systematic process by which the organization is able to identify the positions at the core of its operation and come up with a strategic plan to fill-up these positions with qualified and capable personnel. Identification and development of potential successors for key positions in an organization should be done through a systematic evaluation process and training.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">The organization should have a succession planning to be able to prepare front-line and management staff to step into positions left vacant because of retirement or attrition. It also helps to meet both long term and emergency leadership needs at all levels, ensure continuity of management. Promoting people from within is good for morale and essential to a positive organizational culture, people will want to join and stay with the organization because it develops its own people. And promoting from within encourages people to take on responsibility, assume risks, measure outcomes, and grow through their achievements.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Succession planning also helps to align human resources with the strategic directions of the organization, clarifies each internal candidate\'s strengths, weaknesses, and opportunities for improvement and access to more and better data on the person\'s performance than you would have with outside candidates.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">At the time of the audit, a copy of the Succession Plan was requested from the Human Resource and Management Section. However, the documents provided were not yet signed, although the Audit Team was informed that it was already forwarded to the Office of the Director. Although the R&amp;D Divisions have initiated their succession plan for the key positions of the Division namely, Chief SRS, Supervising SRS, Senior SRS, and SRS II, it is just a mere listing of names that are ready now and those that are assessed as ready in the next 1-3 years. The documented plan with the names of potential leaders needs clearly present the competencies and qualities that need to be developed to prepare them to step up to the role they are likely to assume in case of retirement of the personnel occupying key positions. There is an immediate need to establish a formal mechanism, procedures, and guidelines to ensure succession planning is done with evaluation and training (e.g., coaching and mentoring). Samples of the succession plans submitted are attached in <strong>Annex O</strong>.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt; text-align: justify;\">Based on their PSIPOP as of June 30, 2019, the following are list of key positions that are to be vacated in the next five (5) years due to compulsory retirement:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Table __: Key Positions that are to be Vacated in the next five (5) Years</span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 752px;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 47px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center; height: 47px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Position</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center; height: 47px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">SG</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center; height: 47px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Division</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; text-align: center; height: 47px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Age</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 47px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; height: 47px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Administrative Officer V</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; height: 47px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">18</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; height: 47px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">AD</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; height: 47px; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">63</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 47px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; height: 47px;\"><span style=\"fo