(24, '1', 10, '', '5', 'Finance and Management Division', ' ', 'Account Reconciliation', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Reconciling Items are not immediately recorded in the Accounting books</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Section 20 of Executive Order No. 128 &ldquo;Reorganizing the National Science and Technology Authority&rdquo; provides that the ITDI shall have the following functions:</span></p>\r\n<ol style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Undertake applied research and development to develop technologies and technological innovations in the field of industrial manufacturing, mineral processing and energy;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Undertake the transfer of research results directly to end-users or preferably via linkage units of other government agencies;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Undertake technical services, such as but not limited to, standards, analytical, and calibration services mandated by law od as needed by industry; and</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Conduct training and provide technical advisory and consultancy services to industry clientele and end-users</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Based on the list of bank accounts submitted during the audit, it was discussed that the Institute maintains two (2) current accounts: 1822-1028-63 for the ITDI Training Account and 1822-1028-95 for their Payroll Account. The Training Account was created aligned with the ITDI&rsquo;s mandate presented above.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Bank Reconciliation Statements showed an adjusted balance of P275,490.31 and P387,019.87 as of December 31, 2018 <strong>(Annex S) </strong>and May 31, 2019 <strong>(Annex T)</strong>, respectively. However, as of the time of audit, the items tagged as &ldquo;Debit Memos&rdquo; were still not adjusted in the book of accounts maintained by the Accounting Unit. As reported in the bank reconciliation statement, these debit memos in favor of the Bureau of Customs amounted to a total of P430,821.00 as of May 31, 2019 and broken down as follows:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Table __: Reconciling Items for the ITDI Training Account</span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Date</strong></span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Amount</strong></span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Remarks</strong></span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">August 2, 2017</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">10,099.00</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"6\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Debit Memos- Bureau of Customs</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">March 22, 2018</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">8,728.00</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">August 17, 2018</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">116,058.00</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">May 15, 2019</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">12,045.00</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">May 15, 2019</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">270,405.00</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">May 28, 2019</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">13,486.00</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Total</strong></span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>430,821.00</strong></span></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 33.3333%; text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', '', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-15 10:07:33', '2019-11-26 14:33:55', '0', '3', ' '),
(25, '1', 7, '', '5', 'Finance and Management Division', ' ', 'Grant and Liquidation of Cash Advances', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Late Liquidation and Grant of Overlapping Cash Advances</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 provides that the general guidelines in liquidating cash advances relating to travel allowances is within 30 days after the return of the official/employee concerned to his official station for local travel and within 60 days after the return of the official/employee concerned to the Philippines in the case of foreign travel.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">The same COA Circular and Section 14, Chapter 6 of GAM Volume 1 further specified that &ldquo;No cash advance shall be allowed to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him/her is first settled/liquidated or a proper accounting thereof is made.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Based on the review of Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) of the Institute from year 2015-2018, it was observed that there are delays in liquidating cash advances, both local and foreign travels. At the same time, there are cases in which new requests for cash advances are granted despite having unliquidated balances.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">During the interview and as verified in their records, delays in liquidation and overlapping of cash advances are caused by frequent travels or ITDI employees. There are times in which travels are scheduled every week which enables them to prepare and submit liquidation reports. Since each travel has different purpose and they need cash to finance their expenses, there are new request for cash advances and these are processed and granted by the Accounting Unit. Although written reminders are sent before the end of the 30 or 60-day period, they still failed to liquidate on time. Cases in point are shown attached in <strong>Annexes U and V</strong>.</span></p>', '', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-15 10:10:38', '2019-11-26 14:37:50', '0', '1', ' '),
(26, '1', 7, '', '5', 'Finance and Management Division', ' ', 'Grant and Liquidation of Cash Advances', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>Granting of Cash advances for salaries</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">During the Audit Team&rsquo;s interview with Finance and Administrative personnel, they have mentioned that the Disbursing Officer is granted with cash advances during the end of the year to pay for the salaries of the contract of service personnel. These are not processed through payroll for they are salaries are paid based on the actual attendance, after deducting lates and absences.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">In order for them not to under and over pay the contract of service personnel, cash advances are granted to the Disbursing Officer. The cash are withdrawn and based on the payroll, these are individually distributed to the personnel after office hours during the last working day of the year. &nbsp;Through the help of the personnel from the Human Resource and Management Section, these are placed in an enveloped and personally handed to the concerned personnel.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">Considering that there are one hundred thirty-three (133) contract of service personnel which are assigned to thirty-two (32) projects, individual payments may be too risky on the part of the Disbursing Office, both on the actual payment and in liquidating the cash advance. This is also an extra work for them for they need to extend up to 8:00PM every last working day of the year just to process and ensure that their employees got their actual salaries before New Year&rsquo;s break.</span></p>', '', ' ', ' ', ' ', '2019-08-15 10:12:12', '2019-08-16 14:55:40', '0', '1', ' ');
